<methodology slug="six-core-principles">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>pm-agile</domain>
    <summary>PMBOK 7 six principles for project decisions: holistic view, value, quality, accountability, sustainability, empowerment. Pre-commitment audit before execution.</summary>
    <category>pmbok</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>pmbok7</tag>
      <tag>principles</tag>
      <tag>decision-making</tag>
      <tag>governance</tag>
      <tag>audit</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Six Core Principles (PMBOK 7)</title>

    <summary>PMBOK 7 defines six guiding principles for every project management decision: Adopt Holistic View, Focus on Value, Embed Quality, Lead Accountably, Integrate Sustainability, and Build Empowered Teams. Each principle acts as a pre-commitment heuristic — run the six-question audit before committing to a plan, scope change, or architectural decision to surface violations before they compound.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Process-based PM produces compliance but not necessarily value. Principle-based framing forces the PM and agent to answer "why is this decision good?" for each of six dimensions rather than checking boxes. A mandatory principle audit run before commitment catches value drift, quality debt, and unaccountable decisions at the cheapest moment — before execution.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Validating a PM decision (scope cut, scope add, vendor choice) against principle-based heuristics before committing.</item>
        <item>Auditing an existing project plan to find which guiding principle is being violated.</item>
        <item>Bootstrapping a constitution.md or charter for a new project with first-principles framing.</item>
        <item>Coaching a junior PM on why a recommendation is sound, not just what to do.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure tactical work (sprint board updates, status reports) — principles add overhead with no decision content.</item>
        <item>Compliance-driven projects where regulatory mandates already prescribe behavior.</item>
        <item>Emergency incident response — use OODA or incident runbooks instead.</item>
        <item>Running on every issue; gate to decisions worth meaningful scope or budget impact.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="using-principles-as-pre-commitment-heuristics">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run the six-principle audit before committing to any non-trivial PM decision; auditing after execution recovers nothing.</statement>
        <rationale>Principles function as pre-commitment devices; they catch violations at the cheapest moment (before execution) rather than at the most expensive (after delivery).</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="1-adopt-holistic-view">
      <p>See the project as part of a larger system: organization, portfolio, market, and ecosystem. Decisions that optimize locally often suboptimize the whole.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Application question: "Does this decision consider upstream and downstream effects outside our project boundary?"</item>
        <item>Violation pattern: shipping a feature that solves this project's problem while creating integration debt for three adjacent systems</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="2-focus-on-value">
      <p>Deliver outcomes (user or business results), not just outputs (artifacts or features). Measure value realization explicitly, not by assumption.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Application question: "Can we measure the value this delivers, and to whom?"</item>
        <item>Violation pattern: 100% delivery rate against scope with 30% outcomes realized — "Focus on Value" is not honored without measurable success criteria</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Define at least one project-specific KPI for "value" before starting execution (e.g., NPS+activation, escaped defects, revenue uplift).</statement>
        <rationale>"Focus on Value" without a measurement contract becomes virtue signaling that no one can act on.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="3-embed-quality">
      <p>Quality is built in from the start, not tested in at the end. Covers both product quality (defect rate, performance) and process quality (review rigor, observability).</p>
      <list>
        <item>Application question: "Where is quality verified in the workflow — and is it before or after cost is committed?"</item>
        <item>Violation pattern: equating "Embed Quality" with "add tests" while skipping code review, observability, and runbooks</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="4-lead-accountably">
      <p>Ethical, transparent leadership with clear decision rights. Accountability requires naming who decides, not just who recommends.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Application question: "Is there a named person accountable for this decision, and do they have the authority to make it?"</item>
        <item>Violation pattern: committee decisions with no single accountable — everyone agrees in the room, no one owns the outcome</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="5-integrate-sustainability">
      <p>Consider environmental, social, and economic impact. Requires concrete metrics; "we care about sustainability" without numbers is insufficient.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Application question: "What is the measurable environmental or social impact of this deliverable, and is it acceptable?"</item>
        <item>Violation pattern: skipping the sustainability question entirely in tech projects because it feels irrelevant — cloud carbon, data retention, accessibility all count</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="6-build-empowered-teams">
      <p>Trust, autonomy, and collaboration. Empowerment without explicit decision rights is hollow — teams need to know what they can decide without escalation.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Application question: "What decisions can this team make autonomously today, and is that boundary documented?"</item>
        <item>Violation pattern: claiming empowerment while requiring PM sign-off on every PR merge or minor scope decision</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="priority-when-principles-conflict">
      <rule>
        <statement>When two principles conflict, weight them by project type — a regulated medical product weights Embed Quality 5/5; an internal hackathon weights Focus on Value 5/5 — and document the weighting in constitution.md.</statement>
        <rationale>The six principles have no built-in priority order; without project-level weighting, the most vocal stakeholder's preferred principle wins by default.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="audit-protocol">
      <rule>
        <statement>Force the audit to identify at least one WARN or FAIL; an all-PASS audit is a signal of bias, not health.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs and humans both mark every principle PASS to be agreeable; a mandatory non-PASS prevents the audit from becoming a rubber stamp.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Separate the audit step from the decision step; do not let the same agent or person both review and recommend in one turn.</statement>
        <rationale>Combined review-and-recommend produces confirmation bias: the reviewer unconsciously justifies their pre-formed recommendation through the audit.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>PASS/WARN/FAIL Definitions:</p>
      <list>
        <item>PASS: principle is fully honored with evidence; no remediation needed</item>
        <item>WARN: principle is partially honored; a specific gap exists with a documented mitigation plan</item>
        <item>FAIL: principle is not honored; no mitigation plan; decision should be reconsidered</item>
      </list>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Audit this <plan|decision|ADR> against the PMBOK 7 six core principles.
For each principle output: PASS / WARN / FAIL + one-sentence evidence.
End with the single highest-risk principle violation and one concrete mitigation.
Force at least one WARN or FAIL; if all pass, explain why with specific evidence.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="weighting-procedure">
      <p>Weight principles 1-5 per project type and document in constitution.md. Weighting is not permanent — re-weight at major project milestones.</p>
      <p>Example weightings:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Regulated medical product: Embed Quality 5, Lead Accountably 5, Holistic View 4</item>
        <item>Internal hackathon: Focus on Value 5, Build Empowered Teams 4, others 2-3</item>
        <item>Sustainability-mandated public project: Integrate Sustainability 5, Lead Accountably 4</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Name one accountable human per principle; principles without owners drift regardless of weighting.</statement>
        <rationale>A highly weighted principle without an owner is still nobody's job; accountability converts weight into action.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="gate-calibration">
      <p>Running the audit on every issue creates noise and reduces compliance. Gate principle audits to decisions that cross significance thresholds:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Scope changes exceeding X% of baseline (set per project in constitution.md)</item>
        <item>Budget changes exceeding Y amount</item>
        <item>Architecture decisions affecting more than one team</item>
        <item>Vendor or tool selections</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent synthesizes the audit and the recommendation in the same prompt turn.</description>
        <reason>Produces confirmation bias; the reviewer unconsciously justifies their pre-formed recommendation through audit language.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent equates "Embed Quality" exclusively with adding tests.</description>
        <reason>Process quality (review rigor, observability, runbooks) is equally within scope; test-only framing misses systemic quality gaps.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent skips "Integrate Sustainability" because it seems irrelevant to tech work.</description>
        <reason>Cloud carbon, data retention periods, and accessibility all count as sustainability dimensions in PMBOK 7; skipping produces an incomplete audit.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Treat the principles as preconditions, not afterthoughts: run the audit before commitment, not at retrospective.</item>
        <item>For each principle, define one project-specific KPI (e.g., "value" = NPS+activation; "quality" = escaped defects).</item>
        <item>Always name the accountable human for each principle; principles need owners or they drift.</item>
        <item>Re-weight principles per project — a regulated medical product weights "quality" 5/5; an internal hackathon weights "value" 5/5.</item>
        <item>Couple "build empowered teams" with explicit decision-rights (e.g., who can approve scope change, who can ship without review).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Use the principles as a mandatory checklist that an agent runs over any non-trivial PM decision. The agent answers each of the six prompts with evidence; humans review the violations. Anchor the principles in the project's constitution.md so they aren't restated each time.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-pm-agent — runs the six-principle audit on a draft plan or decision.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — flags any task that fails the value/quality principles before execution.</item>
        <item>General Claude subagent — produces ADR-style "principle review" appended to design docs.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Prompt patterns:</p>
      <p>"Audit this &lt;plan|decision|ADR&gt; against the PMBOK 7 six core principles. For each principle output: PASS / WARN / FAIL + one-sentence evidence. End with the single highest-risk principle violation and one concrete mitigation."</p>
      <p>"Given the project context in &lt;constitution.md&gt;, weight the six principles for this project (1=low, 5=high) and justify each weight in one sentence. Output as a yaml block."</p>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-where-it-fails">
      <p>PMBOK 7 principles are powerful but abstract. Understand these limitations:</p>
      <list>
        <item>The six principles are intentionally abstract; teams reach different conclusions from the same principle.</item>
        <item>"Focus on Value" without measurable success criteria becomes virtue signaling.</item>
        <item>"Sustainability" is the most-skipped principle in tech projects — easy to wave off.</item>
        <item>Provides no priority order between principles when they conflict (e.g., quality vs. value-speed).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/pmbok7-audit.sh" purpose="Shell script: emits a markdown audit table for a decision (six-row PASS/WARN/FAIL form)."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/pmbok-guide-standards"/>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/disciplined-agile"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
